sql:
SELECT *
FROM registers
WHERE type IN ('RW', 'RO');

SELECT COUNT(*) AS write_access_count
FROM register_access
WHERE user_id = 1 AND access_type = 'write';

SELECT privilege_id 
FROM privileges 
WHERE privilege_name = 'Privileged';

external_knowledge:
Frequently accessed: more than 3 times;
Significant access rights: higher privilege level;
Powerful users: user with the highest privilege level for each register.

sql:
SELECT ra.register_id, u.role, ra.mode_id
FROM register_access AS ra
JOIN users AS u ON ra.user_id = u.user_id;

external_knowledge:
Tech enthusiasts here refer to the users in the system;
Delved into reading implies the users have accessed registers through read operations;
The most registers for each type of microcontroller model they've explored means the query is focused on the quantity of registers accessed by read operations grouped by the microcontroller model each user interacts with.

sql:
SELECT u.user_name, ra.access_date
FROM users u
INNER JOIN register_access ra ON u.user_id = ra.user_id;
